🔷 3. Problem Statement

To build a machine learning model that predicts weather conditions such as temperature or rainfall based on input parameters like humidity, pressure, and wind speed, and deploy it using MLOps practices.

🔷 4. Tools & Technologies
Python
Git
DVC
MLflow
FastAPI
Docker
GitHub Actions / Jenkins
Microsoft Azure Machine Learning / Google Vertex AI
🔷 5. Theory

MLOps (Machine Learning Operations) is a practice that combines machine learning, DevOps, and data engineering to automate and manage the ML lifecycle.

In weather prediction:

Historical weather data is used
Models learn patterns
Pipeline ensures continuous improvement

MLOps provides:

Automation
Reproducibility
Scalability
Continuous monitoring
\
🔷 DETAILED PIPELINE (STEP-BY-STEP EXPLANATION)
🔶 1. Problem Definition

This is the starting point of the pipeline.

✔ What is done:
Define objective:
Predict temperature (Regression)
Predict rainfall (Classification)
✔ Example:
Input: temperature, humidity, wind speed
Output: rain (Yes/No)
✔ Importance:
Determines:
Model type
Evaluation metrics
Data requirements

👉 Without clear definition, pipeline fails.

🔶 2. Data Collection
✔ Sources:
Weather APIs
Historical datasets
Meteorological stations
✔ Features collected:
Temperature
Humidity
Pressure
Wind speed
✔ Importance:
High-quality data → high accuracy
More data → better generalization
🔶 3. Data Versioning
✔ Tools:
Git → for code
DVC → for datasets
✔ What happens:
Track dataset changes
Store dataset versions
Maintain history
✔ Importance:
Reproducibility
Rollback capability
Consistency
🔶 4. Data Preprocessing

Raw weather data is noisy and incomplete.

✔ Steps:
Handle missing values (mean/median)
Remove duplicates
Normalize/scale data
Feature engineering
✔ Example:
Convert date → day, month
Create new features like average humidity
✔ Importance:
Clean data improves model performance
🔶 5. Model Training
✔ Algorithms:
Linear Regression → temperature
Random Forest → rainfall
✔ Process:
Split dataset:
80% training
20% testing
Train model on training data
✔ Output:
Trained model

👉 Model learns patterns from data

🔶 6. Experiment Tracking
✔ Tool:
MLflow
✔ Tracks:
Hyperparameters
Accuracy / RMSE
Model files
✔ Importance:
Compare multiple models
Select best model
Maintain experiment history
🔶 7. Model Evaluation
✔ Metrics:
Accuracy (classification)
RMSE (regression)
Precision & Recall
✔ Purpose:
Check model performance
Avoid overfitting

👉 Only best model proceeds

🔶 8. Model Registry
✔ What happens:
Store model in MLflow registry
Maintain versions:
v1, v2, v3
✔ Features:
Stage transitions (staging → production)
Rollback support

👉 Ensures controlled deployment

🔶 9. API Development
✔ Tool:
FastAPI
✔ What happens:
Convert model into REST API
✔ Example:
Input: humidity=80, temp=30
Output: Rain = Yes
✔ Importance:
Makes model usable by applications
🔶 10. Containerization
✔ Tool:
Docker
✔ What is done:
Package:
Model
API
Dependencies
✔ Benefits:
Same environment everywhere
Easy deployment

👉 Solves compatibility issues

🔶 11. CI/CD Pipeline
✔ Tools:
GitHub Actions
Jenkins
✔ CI (Continuous Integration):
Test code automatically
✔ CD (Continuous Deployment):
Deploy model automatically
✔ Importance:
Reduces manual work
Faster updates
🔶 12. Deployment
✔ Platforms:
Microsoft Azure Machine Learning
Google Vertex AI
✔ Output:
Live API endpoint

👉 Users can access predictions online

🔶 13. Monitoring
✔ What is tracked:
Model accuracy
Prediction errors
Data drift
✔ Example:

Weather patterns change → model accuracy drops

👉 Detect problems early

🔶 14. Retraining
✔ When:
Accuracy decreases
New data available
✔ What is done:
Retrain model
Update version

👉 Ensures continuous improvement

